  "Related Work": "While there have been numerous studies on optimizing machine learning models for inference speed, few have focused specifically on the optimization of CUDA kernels for commodity GPUs. Existing work has often relied on theoretical models or simulations, rather than empirical measurements on actual hardware. This proposal builds on the understanding that kernel-level optimizations can have a significant impact on inference speed, and seeks to explore this area in more depth.",
  "Abstract": "This proposal presents a novel approach to optimizing machine learning inference speed on commodity GPUs. By focusing on the optimization of CUDA kernels for memory-bandwidth utilization and tensor-core occupancy, we aim to achieve significant improvements in inference speed without requiring specialized hardware or significant increases in power consumption. Our approach will involve a combination of empirical measurements, kernel-level optimizations, and careful evaluation of the resulting performance improvements. We will use a range of benchmarks and metrics, including latency, throughput, and energy consumption, to evaluate the effectiveness of our approach.",
  "Experiments": "We will conduct a series of experiments to evaluate the effectiveness of our approach. These will include: (1) optimizing CUDA kernels for a range of machine learning models, including convolutional neural networks and recurrent neural networks; (2) evaluating the impact of different kernel-level optimizations on inference speed, including coalesced memory access, register blocking, and tensor-core occupancy; (3) comparing the performance of our optimized kernels to existing state-of-the-art implementations; and (4) evaluating the energy consumption and power draw of our optimized kernels. We will use a range of tools, including nvprof and Nsight, to collect detailed performance metrics and identify areas for further optimization.",
  "Risk Factors and Limitations": "There are several potential risk factors and limitations to our approach. These include: (1) the complexity of optimizing CUDA kernels, which can require significant expertise and experimentation; (2) the potential for limited improvements in inference speed, particularly if the underlying hardware is already well-optimized; and (3) the need to balance optimization for inference speed with other considerations, such as model accuracy and power consumption. To mitigate these risks, we will use a combination of empirical measurements, careful evaluation, and iterative refinement to ensure that our optimizations are effective and robust."
}}
Proposal finalized: {'Name': 'gpu_kernel_opt', 'Title': 'Optimizing CUDA Kernels for Machine Learning Inference on Commodity GPUs', 'Short Hypothesis': 'Carefully optimizing CUDA kernels for memory-bandwidth utilization and tensor-core occupancy can lead to significant improvements in machine learning inference speed on commodity GPUs, without requiring specialized hardware or significant increases in power consumption.', 'Related Work': 'While there have been numerous studies on optimizing machine learning models for inference speed, few have focused specifically on the optimization of CUDA kernels for commodity GPUs. Existing work has often relied on theoretical models or simulations, rather than empirical measurements on actual hardware. This proposal builds on the understanding that kernel-level optimizations can have a significant impact on inference speed, and seeks to explore this area in more depth.', 'Abstract': 'This proposal presents a novel approach to optimizing machine learning inference speed on commodity GPUs. By focusing on the optimization of CUDA kernels for memory-bandwidth utilization and tensor-core occupancy, we aim to achieve significant improvements in inference speed without requiring specialized hardware or significant increases in power consumption. Our approach will involve a combination of empirical measurements, kernel-level optimizations, and careful evaluation of the resulting performance improvements. We will use a range of benchmarks and metrics, including latency, throughput, and energy consumption, to evaluate the effectiveness of our approach.', 'Experiments': 'We will conduct a series of experiments to evaluate the effectiveness of our approach. These will include: (1) optimizing CUDA kernels for a range of machine learning models, including convolutional neural networks and recurrent neural networks; (2) evaluating the impact of different kernel-level optimizations on inference speed, including coalesced memory access, register blocking, and tensor-core occupancy; (3) comparing the performance of our optimized kernels to existing state-of-the-art implementations; and (4) evaluating the energy consumption and power draw of our optimized kernels. We will use a range of tools, including nvprof and Nsight, to collect detailed performance metrics and identify areas for further optimization.', 'Risk Factors and Limitations': 'There are several potential risk factors and limitations to our approach. These include: (1) the complexity of optimizing CUDA kernels, which can require significant expertise and experimentation; (2) the potential for limited improvements in inference speed, particularly if the underlying hardware is already well-optimized; and (3) the need to balance optimization for inference speed with other considerations, such as model accuracy and power consumption. To mitigate these risks, we will use a combination of empirical measurements, careful evaluation, and iterative refinement to ensure that our optimizations are effective and robust.'}
