    "Name": "information_theoretic_model_compression",
    "Title": "Exploring Information-Theoretic Limits of Model Compression in Deep Learning",
    "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that the fundamental limits of model compression in deep learning can be characterized using information-theoretic tools, such as rate-distortion theory and statistical learning theory. By understanding these limits, we can develop more efficient and effective model compression methods.",
    "Related Work": "Recent works, such as EMQ, AMP-ViT, and SNIP, have explored various aspects of model compression, including mixed-precision quantization and adaptive bit-width allocation. However, these works have not explicitly addressed the information-theoretic limits of model compression. Our proposal seeks to fill this gap by providing a rigorous theoretical framework for understanding the fundamental limits of model compression.",
    "Abstract": "Model compression is a crucial technique for deploying deep learning models in resource-constrained environments. However, the fundamental limits of model compression are not well understood. In this proposal, we aim to explore the information-theoretic limits of model compression in deep learning using tools from rate-distortion theory and statistical learning theory. We will develop a theoretical framework for characterizing the trade-off between model complexity and compression ratio, and investigate the role of distortion measures in determining the optimal compression strategy. Our results will provide valuable insights into the theoretical limits of model compression and inform the development of more efficient and effective compression methods.",
    "Experiments": "We will conduct experiments to validate our theoretical framework and investigate the information-theoretic limits of model compression. Specifically, we will: (1) develop a rate-distortion theory-based framework for characterizing the trade-off between model complexity and compression ratio; (2) investigate the role of distortion measures in determining the optimal compression strategy; and (3) evaluate the performance of our compression method on various deep learning models and datasets.",
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": "The main risk factor of this proposal is the complexity of the theoretical framework, which may require significant mathematical derivations and proofs. Additionally, the experimental evaluation of our compression method may require significant computational resources and large datasets. To mitigate these risks, we will: (1) collaborate with experts in information theory and statistical learning theory; (2) develop efficient algorithms and implementations for our compression method; and (3) carefully select datasets and models for experimental evaluation."
